Verilog and VHDL are hardware description languages (HDLs) used for designing and describing digital circuits and systems. Here are the languages used to write Verilog and VHDL:

    Verilog:
        Verilog HDL (or simply Verilog) was initially developed by Gateway Design Automation in the early 1980s. It was later standardized as IEEE 1364 and underwent several revisions, including Verilog-1995, Verilog-2001, Verilog-2005, and SystemVerilog (which is an extension of Verilog).

    Verilog is primarily based on the C programming language and draws many of its syntax and structure from it. It uses concepts such as modules, functions, tasks, procedural blocks, and data types to describe the behavior and structure of digital circuits. Verilog code can be written in a textual format using a text editor.

    VHDL:
        VHDL (VHSIC Hardware Description Language) was developed by the U.S. Department of Defense in the late 1980s as part of the VHSIC (Very High-Speed Integrated Circuit) program. It was standardized as IEEE 1076 and has also undergone revisions, including VHDL-87, VHDL-93, and VHDL-2008.

    VHDL is a strongly typed language and draws its syntax and structure from Ada, a general-purpose programming language. It uses entities, architectures, processes, signals, and components to describe the behavior and structure of digital circuits. VHDL code is typically written in a textual format using a text editor.

Both Verilog and VHDL have their own strengths and are widely used in the digital design industry. The choice between the two often depends on factors such as personal preference, design requirements, and the tools and methodologies used within a specific project or organization.

